Enjoy <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
This week I saw on PlanetEverQuest that Sony Online Entertainment and White Wolf publishing are teaming up to create an EverQuest Pen-and-Paper roleplaying game. That means you can conquer the realms of Norath with graph paper and dice while sitting around a dinner table. <br>
<br>
As we know from previous columns, I Love Roleplaying Games! So while I was skeptical that EQ would make a fun pen-and-paper RPG, I was eager to jump right in. For one thing, I noticed that the EQ RPG would use the standard d20 system, much like Dungeons and Dragons 3rd Edition. I was able to quickly whip up a set of rules and I ran through a sample game with my friends. Below you'll find an actual gameplay session with myself as game master. Joining me is our managing editor John &quot;Warrior&quot; Keefer, our resident cynic Chris &quot;shaithis&quot; Buecheler, and our graphics designer Matt &quot;Kindrak&quot; Chandronait, who is both an avid roleplayer and a wuss. Let's get it on with the hot gaming action! <br>
<br>
A sample game session with the EQ Pen-and-paper RPG <br>
<br>
Fargo the Gaming Master: Okay, the party is all set? Then you step through the broken archway. The stench that assaults your nostrils beyond that foul gate is almost as horrifying as the visage that greets you within that accursed portal. For within you find the cracked stone interior of Grogoth's inner sanctum. Here is where the master performed the dark magicks neccessary to ensure his hated iron grip over the realm. Chains and torches line the flickering red walls, besmeared with the blood of his victims. His throne, made of skin and bone, reeks of magnanimous power. Before it sits a black obsidian altar, upon which grotesque crimes against humanity have been performed. You are the first humans to lay eyes upon this unspeakable place of your own free will, and your terror is mitigated only by the knowledge that the death of Grogoth can bring piece to this shattered land. <br>
<br>
 Warrior: I'm not wasting any time. I draw my sword! <br>
<br>
shaithis: Is the dark lord in the chamber? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Gaming Master: [Rolls some dice] ... no, the Dark Lord Grogoth is already dead. There are [rolls dice] six other people waiting in line for him to respawn so they can kill him and take his l3wt. <br>
<br>
Warrior: Aw, crap. Okay, I'm going to get in line. <br>
<br>
Kindrak: [Starts quietly rolling dice.] <br>
<br>
shaithis: Hey, so if the Dark Lord Grogoth is already dead, why isn't the land free once again? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: Shush! <br>
<br>
shaithis: No really, shouldn't we be partying it up with wenches and mead? How come the land is still black with the stench of his whatsit and stuff? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: Silence! This whole zone has always been under control of the Dark Lord. Who else would drop the Devastation Staff +10? <br>
<br>
Kindrak: [Quietly rolls dice] <br>
<br>
 Warrior: How often does he respawn? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: Every hour. <br>
<br>
 Warrior: Hey, this isn't too bad. Last weekend we spent sixteen hours waiting for the Journeyman's boots. I sit cross-legged on the floor. Can we order a pizza? I mean ... in real life? <br>
<br>
Kindrak: [Quietly rolls dice] <br>
<br>
shaithis: Oh ... oh this is boring. Who's in line waiting to kill Grogoth? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: [Rolls dice] A male half-elven Ranger ... [rolls dice] A female high-elf priestess... <br>
<br>
shaithis: Nice! Is she hot? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: Definitely. She looks like the cover of the box. <br>
<br>
shaithis: ... is she hot in real life? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: [Rolls dice] WHOA! <br>
<br>
shaithis: What whoa? Whoa yes or whoa no? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: I guess you'll never know. <br>
<br>
Kindrak: [Quietly rolls dice] <br>
<br>
 Warrior: Kindrak, what are you doing? <br>
<br>
Kindrak: [Rolls dice] I'm macroing. [Rolls dice.] <br>
<br>
shaithis: Screw this line of people! I want me some Dark Lord l3wt. I'm gonna leave the room and try to get a chain of monsters to follow me. That'll shake everyone up. <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: Okay, you find [rolls dice] a Skeleton Berserker. And ... [rolls dice] four more Skeleton Berserkers. Tough crowd. <br>
<br>
shaithis: I attack them and run back toward the group! <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: Okay, shaithis comes bursting into the room with a chain of skeletons behind him. Oh no! The Dark Lord spawns! Everyone's casting magic. It's pandemonium. Roll your lag resistance rolls. <br>
<br>
Kindrak: Oh CRAP! [Looks at character sheet] You know my computer can't handle all that stuff at once. [Rolls dice] <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: Oh dear. 01. That's a critical failure. Let me roll for results... [Rolls] Kindrak gets disconnected. <br>
<br>
Kindrak: Arrgghhh!! <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: Quiet, we can't hear you when you're offline. By the way, someone else just killed the Dark Lord. <br>
<br>
Warrior: I wish I was a player killer. <br>
<br>
shaithis: This sucks! I'm going home for the night. Do I have to roll to log off? <br>
<br>
Fargo the Game Master: No, but it's the end of the month. So pay up! <br>
<br>
